The trap of perfectionism is all too real. It can be hard to recognize when you’re caught in it, and it can be even harder to break free. But it’s important to remember that perfection is impossible and that it’s okay to make mistakes. Here are a few tips to help you avoid the perfection trap:⁠
⁠
1. Set realistic goals - Be realistic about what you can achieve and give yourself room to make mistakes. Challenge yourself to do your best, but don’t set goals that are impossible to reach.⁠
⁠
2. Celebrate small successes - Don’t focus on perfection. Celebrate the small successes that you make along the way. Allow yourself to recognize and appreciate the progress that you’re making.⁠
⁠
3. Recognize your strengths - Everyone has their own unique set of strengths and weaknesses. Focus on developing your strengths and don’t worry about your weaknesses.⁠
⁠
4. Take breaks - Don’t try to do too much at once. Take breaks and give yourself time to relax and recharge.⁠
⁠
5. Celebrate progress - Focusing on progress, rather than perfection, can be a great way to stay motivated. Celebrate that progress.
⁠
⁠
#perfection #progressmakesperfect #realisticgoals #goalsetting

10 years ago today, my life changed forever. I was induced into a medical coma given a 1% chance to live. My body went into septic shock from a bacteria that got into my bloodstream. I was a healthy 21 yr old & in an instant my world came crashing down. ⁠
⁠
I was in a coma for 6 days, in the ICU for 10, where my family stood by my side hearing the doctors say I may not make it. I laid there in the ICU bed with a tube down my throat hooked up to 9 bags of antibiotics. ⁠
⁠
I remember the experiences I had in the coma, ones so real they are more realistic than the reality I'm living today. Serene, beautiful. ⁠
⁠
I remember the nightmare I woke up to in the hospital bed not realizing what had happened and in so much physical pain. ⁠
⁠
I remember not being able to move, breathe, or speak on my own & remember the vision I held in my mind to try to heal my body through color. (something I share in my book 'Adaptable') ⁠
⁠
This NDE led to years of struggle, heartache, health challenges, and loss. ⁠
⁠
I lost who I was. ⁠
I lost my health. ⁠
I lost my life I had planned for after I graduated college. ⁠
I lost a lot of friends. ⁠
I lost my dream career in fashion. ⁠
I lost my happiness, my smile, but most of all my spirit. ⁠
⁠
But through darkness there is always light if you choose to seek it out. ⁠
⁠
My NDE was followed by a diagnosis for a chronic autoimmune disease which led to many years of struggle. ⁠
⁠
After letting the illness define me for years I decided to stop waiting to get the old "Alexa" back and adapt to what I couldn't control. ⁠
⁠
For so long I believed I'd never be able to travel again and today I'm a speaker & founder who travels to impact others.⁠
I believed I'd never find love again and now I'm married to love of my life.⁠
I believed I'd never be able to achieve my goals and now I found my true passion.⁠
I believed I wouldn't be the happy person I was as a kid & today I make my family laugh daily! 😉 ⁠
⁠
So today help me celebrate LIVING by sharing one small thing you are grateful for. For me it's the sun rays on my skin and my mom by my side, as she saved my life that day 10 years ago. ☀️⁠

Each member gives a quick update on what they need from myself and others⁠
If anything is up for discussion, this is when we will quickly brainstorm and see if we can make a decision on the call⁠
2️⃣ I then give my updates which are focused on⁠
feedback or context behind why we are pivoting or doing something⁠
ideas I’m working on⁠
brainstorming/feedback needed from them⁠
Edits/ changes that I need a team member to make⁠
⁠
And that's about it! I've found this model to work the best right now because it doesn't waste anyone's time, we actually achieve things on the call, and I'm able to keep my team in the know of what I'm working on re-the growth side of the business so they feel included and can also shed their opinion. ⁠

A few fun facts about my twin pregnancy that are common questions I get at least once a week:

💙Do twins run in your family?
Nope! Only fraternal twins are genetic, identical twins are just a .04% chance it can randomly happen.

💙What kind of twins are you having? 
Mo/di twins which means they're identical with one placenta and two amniotic sacs.

💙Did you do IVF or anything to get twins?
Nope! Just randomly happened ! Monozygotic twins happen when one egg splits into two early on after fertilization. 

💙When are you due, you look so tiny for two babies in there?!
Technical due date is actually Oct 1st but full term for twins is 36-38 weeks and docs won't let us go past 38 so they will be here in mid September! 

💙Are you nervous about them being identical? 
Yes! And excited! 

💙Is this your first? 
Yep, first time ever pregnant. 

💙Do you know the gender? 
Boys! 

#32weeks which means the babies will be here in 5.5 weeks or less! 🤯🤯🤯😍😍😍

Mom guilt, let’s talk about it. I knew I’d eventually feel mom guilt as my babies got older just like I know any mama does sometimes (especially those working moms out there!) but I never thought I’d feel it because I’m a twin mom.

I feel it almost every day. When both my babies are crying and want to be held and soothed yet I can only pick up one baby at a time. When one is having a contact nap on me and the other wakes up and sees me and I just feel like they are thinking “what the heck mommy who is that other baby on you and why aren’t you napping with me”. I feel so bad! 

Or even when I’m only taking a photo with one of them, the mom guilt is just always there. And it’s tough because I know it’s important to have individual time with my babies to create that strong bond with each of them but if I’m only with one I feel guilty I’m not spending time with the other one. 

Walking into motherhood is definitely the biggest change of my life and I’m learning each day the type of mom I want to be as well as how to raise my babies the best way I know how. But boy is there a lot of tough emotions and feelings you must work through in the process that I was not ready for! 

Drop a ❤️ if you’ve felt that mom guilt before so I know I’m not alone! (And if you have any advice to release it please feel free to share!) community is so helpful through these changes and I love seeing the mom support love!

Never in my wildest dreams would I have thought I’d be a twin mom. I always thought it had to be genetic but nope, did I learn that quickly. We are amongst the .04% of women who are gifted the blessing of identical twins. It’s random and it’s crazy how it happens. And I have to admit, there’s many times after I found out where I mourned the loss of what I envisioned motherhood to be. 

Everything is built for one baby… doors for a single stroller vs double, mommy and me classes, swings at the park, coffee shop tables, bathrooms to change babies, restaurants, the big dressing room at stores… and so it’s been a tough transition adapting to this new vision of motherhood. But I also couldn’t imagine it any other way. This is all I know and I’m so beyond in love with my babies. 

I know I’m so lucky and just seeing two babies smile at you will melt your heart. But I wanted to be open and transparent that it’s tough! I can’t help but sometimes be envious of singleton parents when they seem to easily be able to travel or be out of the house alone with their one baby.  Or even the ease of only needing one family member to babysit vs logistics with needing 2 people to watch 2 babies. (Because 2 vs 1 for sure wears out mom and dad when we are alone!)

It’s a beautiful yet challenging rewarding adventure as a twin mom. And while motherhood is veryyyy different from what I always imagined it to be, I’m so grateful I got this gift of 2 beautiful healthy babies. 

 And for other moms of multiples in my community, I hope this post helps you know that you’re not alone in your feelings! 

(And this post is not meant to say one baby is easy because I know it for sure is not! Just sharing some of my own motherhood challenges and I know all moms have their own and it’s amazing we are all still doing the thing! Gotta support and not judge one another 💕)

Dear future mama, your life is about to forever change and although it’ll be different, it’s a shift you’re meant to go through. You may not recognize yourself at first. The sweats you’ve been wearing all week with spit up on both shoulders and your clipped up hair that hasn’t been washed in a week may make you feel a loss of identity. You wonder when you’ll feel pretty again. But know this shift is the greatest one you’ll ever experience. It’ll be more challenging than you can possibly imagine. But you’ll discover how strong you truly are and how strong you can be. You’ll feel so happy and filled with love while at the same time sad. Sad of how quickly time is already passing and how your little one is growing without slowing down. Sad for how your life and career is different now. But at the same time, you know this is everything you’ve ever dreamt about. It’s okay to feel these two opposing feelings. Know you’re not alone. You will become a master multitasker. You will find purpose in raising your little ones. While it’ll sometimes feel impossible as you only have two hands, you’ll figure out how to make things happen in the most creative ways. Life looks different now but it is in these moments that we become the woman we are meant to be. The mother our children need us to be. You will find yourself again. Not your old self, but your new self. And that person you become will be more you than you could’ve imagined. Hang in there. Have patience. Stay calm. And know all is working in your favor. You are becoming the most amazing woman and this new identity is one you’ll forever be grateful for. 

Love the new stage in all its ups and downs because you were made for it. God gives you what you can handle, even when you’re in the thick of it and have no clue how you will handle it. You can. You will. You got this.

It’s crazy how excited we get when our baby hits a new milestone. They start cooing, can lift their heads during tummy time, or recognize their own name and we go nuts. We praise them and encourage them and are so happy for them. 

Yet we never do that for ourselves.

We get a promotion at work, create an awesome reel on social media, learn how to play an instrument, or just nail your at home latte making. Sure we may feel happy for a brief moment but then we are looking ahead at all the things we want to achieve yet haven’t yet vs truly celebrating all the little things in life. 

Being a mom has helped me appreciate the little things so much more. Life doesn’t need these big extravagant things to make it wonderful. Laying on the floor with your babies and just watching them grow is the most special thing. 

Celebrate the little milestones in your babies life but also in your own.
